<subSubSection id="C30043C2A53165460DEFF1DFFECBFD6F" pageId="3" pageNumber="291" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BA51049A53165460DEFF1DFFC3EFE6B" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,788]" pageId="3" pageNumber="291">
<emphasis id="B96ECC5BA53165460DEFF1DFFD03FF5C" bold="true" box="[199,679,151,176]" pageId="3" pageNumber="291">
<emphasis id="B96ECC5BA53165460DEFF1DFFEF6FF43" box="[199,338,151,175]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="291" reason="1">Description.</emphasis>
External morphology of adult
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13210CCCA53165460F9DF1DFFD57FF5C" box="[693,755,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1956,1978]" captionTargetBox="[165,1435,185,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-28@1.[152,1436,182,1930]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Epimecia (1–3) and Lophoterges (4–8) spp.: adults. Depositories of specimens: 1, 2, 5–8—BBT; 3—STP; 4—AFM." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406514" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406514/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="291">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Wingspan of female 
<typeStatus id="54A1AEEBA53165460ECCF1DFFBE5FF43" box="[996,1089,151,175]" pageId="3" pageNumber="291">holotype</typeStatus>
<quantity id="4CE2BDACA5316546096FF1D0FB37FF43" box="[1095,1171,152,176]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="291" unit="mm" value="30.0">30 mm</quantity>
, forewing length 
<quantity id="4CE2BDACA53165460864F1D0FA3DFF43" box="[1356,1433,152,176]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="3" pageNumber="291" unit="mm" value="14.0">14 mm</quantity>
. Female antenna filiform. Forewing elongated, only slightly triangular, nearly regularly oblong in shape with rounded apex. Ground colour of frons, thorax and forewing pale ash-grey mixed with lighter and darker scales, terminal area slightly suffused with some fine golden shine. Antemedial and postmedial fasciae obscure, indistinct. Orbicular and reniform spots moderately remarkable, blackish, encircled with dirty-white scales. Forewing cilia short, mixed with lighter and darker scales. Hindwing lighter than forewing, dirty white, terminally widely shadowed with darker scales, veins also suffused with darker scales; discal spot indistinct; cilia light dirty-white.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA51049A53165460DEFF0DCFA30FDB3" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,788]" pageId="3" pageNumber="291">
<emphasis id="B96ECC5BA53165460DEFF0DCFE28FE47" bold="true" box="[199,396,403,428]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="291" reason="1">Female genitalia.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13210CCCA53165460CB4F0DBFE7BFE40" box="[412,479,403,428]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–15" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1956,1978]" captionTargetBox="[176,1414,188,1917]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[164,1424,182,1931]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 9–15. Epimecia (9, 10) and Lophoterges (11–15) spp.: female genitalia. Depositories of specimens: 9, 12–15—BBT; 10— HNHM (photo by V.S. Kononenko); 11—AFM." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406516" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406516/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="291">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
) Papillae anales oblong, not sclerotised, rather large and moderately setose. Apophyses anteriores relatively long, thin, apophyses posteriores medium-long, somewhat thicker than apophyses anteriores. Ostium bursae broad. Antrum broad, calyculate with weakly sclerotized lateral margins. Ductus bursae narrow, flattened, its posterior end at the connection with antrum membranous; sclerotized anterior section of ductus bursae elongated, heavily sclerotized with membranous left lateral margin, gently curved, its anterior bar strongly curved and extends to the cervix bursae. Corpus bursae broad, nearly globular, membranous. Cervix bursae broadly conical with rounded tip, gelatinous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA51049A53165460DEFF323FECBFD6F" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,788]" box="[199,367,619,643]" pageId="3" pageNumber="291">Male unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30043C2A53165460DEFF3C7FAFBFD03" pageId="3" pageNumber="291" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BA51049A53165460DEFF3C7FAFBFD03" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,788]" pageId="3" pageNumber="291">
<emphasis id="B96ECC5BA53165460DEFF3C7FDA2FD4B" box="[199,518,655,680]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="291" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B96ECC5BA53165460DEFF3C7FE5BFD4B" bold="true" box="[199,511,655,680]" pageId="3" pageNumber="291">Distribution and bionomics</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
The new species is known only from its type-locality, white gypsum-hills with scanty vegetation emerging from a vast steppe (
<figureCitation id="13210CCCA53165460F60F3FBFD3CFD27" box="[584,664,691,715]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="3.[151,244,1801,1823]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,813,1777]" captionTargetId="figure-301@3.[151,1435,813,1777]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 16. Kazakhstan, Prov. Almaty, 10 km N of Tekes, 2000 m, N43°56′, E079°59′, 20.VII.2009, the type locality of Epimecia tekes sp. n. (photo by Balázs Benedek)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406518" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406518/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="291">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
). The single specimen has been found early in the morning sitting on the white screen illuminated by a 125W mercury-vapour bulb. The preimaginal stages and the foodplant are unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30043C2A53165460DEFF3B4FB8EFCFF" box="[199,1066,763,788]" pageId="3" pageNumber="291" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BA51049A53165460DEFF3B4FB8EFCFF" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,788]" box="[199,1066,763,788]" pageId="3" pageNumber="291">
<emphasis id="B96ECC5BA53165460DEFF3B4FEECFCF8" bold="true" box="[199,328,764,788]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="291" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
